tOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vast majority of primary hyperparathyroidism cases (approximately 85%) are caused by a \u003Cstrong\u003Esolitary parathyroid adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The remaining cases are distributed among other causes: \u003Cstrong\u003Eparathyroid hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E (10-15%), \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple parathyroid adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E (2-3%), \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 1\u003C/strong\u003E (2-4%), and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparathyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (less than 1%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition is characterized by excessive production of parathyroid hormone that occurs independently of the body\u0027s calcium regulation mechanisms. Many patients are identified through routine blood tests that reveal elevated calcium levels before they develop symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A benign tumor of a single parathyroid gland (adenoma) is responsible for about 85% of primary hyperparathyroidism cases.","Genetic syndromes like MEN1 can cause parathyroid gland dysfunction, though this is much less common.","In primary hyperparathyroidism, the parathyroid glands produce excess hormone regardless of blood calcium levels."],"references":["Casella C, Guarneri C, Campanile M, Adhoute X, Gelera PP, Morandi R. Surgical treatment of tertiary hyperparathyroidism: does one fit for all? Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2023 Nov 2;14:1226917. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2023.1226917. PMID: 38027172; PMCID: PMC10652876","Madkhali T, Alhefdhi A, Chen H, Elfenbein D. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Ulus Cerrahi Derg. 2016 Mar 1;32(1):58-66. doi: 10.5152/UCD.2015.3032. PMID: 26985167; PMCID: PMC4771429","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55941"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15612"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55941"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T14:42:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T14:43:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8303"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70477"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdA